STEP 7 – Find Object Groups
==================================================================
Object groups allow multiple networks to be grouped
together. The VPN ACL may reference an object group
instead of individual networks.

Automation reads the object group to identify which
object networks are used in the VPN.


Command:show run object-group id <group_name>
--------------------------------------------------


Syntax
--------------------------------------------------
object-group network <group_name>
 network-object object <object_name>

Example
--------------------------------------------------
show run object-group id AZURE_PA_NET

Example Output
--------------------------------------------------
object-group network AZURE_PA_NET
 network-object object 10.2.5.0_24
 network-object object 10.2.6.0_24

==================================================================
Dynamic Object-Group Detection
==================================================================

Why
--------------------------------------------------
In production environments, the object-group name
is not fixed. Different VPN configurations may use
different object-group names.

Example:
AZURE_PA_NET
AWS_REMOTE_NET
REMOTE_SUBNETS

Therefore automation must dynamically identify the
object-group name from the VPN ACL configuration.


Step 1 – Read VPN ACL
--------------------------------------------------
Command

show run access-list <acl_name>

Example

show run access-list outside_cryptomap_1


Example Output

access-list outside_cryptomap_1 extended permit ip
192.168.10.0 255.255.255.0
object-group AZURE_PA_NET


From this ACL line automation detects:

object-group AZURE_PA_NET


Step 2 – Extract Object Group Name
--------------------------------------------------
Python code parses the ACL line and extracts the
object-group name.


Code Example with Comment
--------------------------------------------------

acl_output = connection.send_command(
    "show run access-list outside_cryptomap_1"
)

group_name = None

for line in acl_output.splitlines():

    if "object-group" in line:

        parts = line.split()

        group_name = parts[-1]   # extract object-group name


Result

group_name = AZURE_PA_NET


Step 3 – Run Object Group Command Dynamically
--------------------------------------------------

command = f"show run object-group id {group_name}"

output = connection.send_command(command)


Final Command Executed

show run object-group id AZURE_PA_NET


==================================================================
Summary
==================================================================

1. Automation first finds the ACL used in the VPN
   from the crypto map.

   Command:show run crypto map


2. It reads the ACL to check if an object-group
   is used instead of direct subnets.

   Command:show run access-list <acl_name>


3. If an object-group is found, the automation
   extracts the object-group name dynamically.

   Example:object-group AZURE_PA_NET


4. Then it reads the object-group configuration
   to get all object names.

   Command:
   show run object-group id <group_name>


5. Finally, it reads the object network definitions
   from the running configuration to convert object
   names into real subnet values.

   Command:
   show run


Result:Automation identifies the actual remote subnets
used in the VPN configuration.
Object-group name is NOT hardcoded.

Automation flow:

show run crypto map
        │
        ▼
Find ACL name
        │
        ▼
show run access-list <ACL>
        │
        ▼
Detect object-group
        │
        ▼
show run object-group id <group_name>
        │
        ▼
Get object names
        │
        ▼
show run
        │
        ▼
Get real subnet
